==English==

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|head=[[very]] [[well]]|-}}

# {{&lit|very|well|lang=en}}
#: ''I'm feeling '''very well''' today.''

===Adverb===
{{en-adv|head=[[very]] [[well]]}}

# {{&lit|very|well|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|He managed the company '''very well'''.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|He understood '''very well''' that there might be difficulties.}}
#*{{RQ:WBsnt IvryGtP}}
#*:Thus, when he drew up instructions in lawyer language, he expressed the important words by an initial, a medial, or a final consonant, and made scratches for all the words between; his clerks, however, understood him '''very well'''.
# {{context|idiomatic|lang=en}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to weaken the effect of certain [[modal verb]]s.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|It may '''very well''' rain this afternoon.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|I can't '''very well''' talk to you and concentrate on sanding this at the same time.}}

====Usage notes====
* {{sense|used to weaken the effect of modal verbs}} The improbability introduced by {{term|may}} is weaker in {{term||It may very well rain}} than in {{term||It may rain}}. Likewise, the impossibility meant by {{term|can't}} is weaker in {{term||I can't very well talk}} than in {{term||I can't talk}}.

===Interjection===
{{en-interj|head=[[very]] [[well]]}}

# {{context|idiomatic|dated|formal|lang=en}} Indicating [[acceptance]], often with [[resignation]] or [[acquiescence]], of a statement or situation.
#: A: ''I don't want to go today.''
#: B: '''''Very well'''. Let's go tomorrow, then.''

